'''{{ill|Yuga Shrine|ja|瑜伽神社}}''' is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社}} located on {{ill|Mount Yuga|ja|瑜伽山}} in {{ill|Takabatake-chō|ja|高畑町}}, {{ill|Nara City|ja|奈良市}}, {{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県}}.

== 由緒 ==
According to shrine tradition, {{ill|Asuka Kannabi|ja|飛鳥神奈備}} was relocated to this area when {{ill|Heijō-kyō|ja|平城京}} was established, and the mountain came to be known as **Asuka-yama of Heijō**.{{sfn|奈良市史 社寺編|p=81}} Originally, it served as a **guardian shrine** (鎮守, chinju) of {{ill|Gango-ji Zenjō-in|ja|元興寺禅定院}}, protecting its **kimon** (鬼門, unlucky direction). Later, when {{ill|Daijō-in|ja|大乗院}}, a sub-temple of {{ill|Kōfuku-ji|ja|興福寺}}, was built at the mountain's base, the shrine became its **guardian deity** and was venerated by the {{ill|Fujiwara clan|ja|藤原氏}}.{{sfn|奈良市史 社寺編|p=81}}

An entry from December 30, *Meiō* 3 (1494) in the *Daijō-in Jisha Zasshiki* (大乗院寺社雑事記) states that "Ima-miya Palace" (今宮殿) was temporarily thatched, identifying it as **this shrine**. It was called "Ima-miya" to distinguish it from its supposed original shrine in **Asuka**.{{sfn|奈良市史 社寺編|p=81}} The name **Yuga Shrine** was adopted relatively recently.{{sfn|奈良市史 社寺編|p=81}}

== 歴史 ==
However, there are doubts about this traditional account.{{sfn|『大乗院寺社雑事記』にみえる瀧蔵社と新宮社|p=46}}

=== 今宮 ===
The traditional claim that "Ima-miya" referred to the original Asuka shrine is challenged by historical records. According to *Daijō-in Jisha Zasshiki*, **Ima-miya** was actually founded in *Entoku* 2 (1490) by {{ill|Jinson|ja|尋尊}}, the abbot of Daijō-in. He received permission to enshrine the **Five Deities of Kasuga** (春日五所明神) at **Mount Kion** (鬼薗山).{{sfn|寺院神社大辞典|p=793}} The enshrinement ceremony was held on June 21 of the same year.{{sfn|寺院神社大辞典|p=793}}

The shrine’s original location was **Mount Kion**, not Mount Yuga.{{sfn|『大乗院寺社雑事記』にみえる瀧蔵社と新宮社|pp=46-47}} This is further supported by Edo-period records, which still listed "Ima-miya" at **Mount Kion**. The shrine likely disappeared when Daijō-in was dismantled in the early Meiji period.{{sfn|『大乗院寺社雑事記』にみえる瀧蔵社と新宮社|p=47}}

=== 新宮 ===
Mount Yuga, historically called **Seihōin-yama**, was home to **Shingū Shrine**, which enshrined **Kakuson**, the twelfth abbot of Daijō-in.{{sfn|『大乗院寺社雑事記』にみえる瀧蔵社と新宮社|p=42}} The shrine's origins and disappearance are unknown.{{sfn|『大乗院寺社雑事記』にみえる瀧蔵社と新宮社|p=43}}

=== 天満天神と稲荷社 ===
The original **guardian shrine** of **Gango-ji Zenjō-in** was **Tenmangū Shrine**, which remained Daijō-in’s protector.{{sfn|『大乗院寺社雑事記』にみえる瀧蔵社と新宮社|p=47}}

In *Kyōhō* 3 (1718), a shrine caretaker received a divine dream and restored a **small Inari shrine** within **Tenmangū Shrine**.{{sfn|『大乗院寺社雑事記』にみえる瀧蔵社と新宮社|p=48}} Since Yuga Shrine and **Inari shrines** both enshrine **Ukanomitama-no-Mikoto**, it is speculated that this Inari Shrine later became known as Yuga Shrine.{{sfn|『大乗院寺社雑事記』にみえる瀧蔵社と新宮社|p=48}}

=== 瑜伽山城 ===
This area is also believed to be the site of **Yuga Castle** (瑜伽山城), also called **Seihōin-yama Castle** or **Kion-zan Castle**, with remains of wide terraces and moats still visible.{{sfn|奈良市史 社寺編|p=81}}

== 境内 ==
The shrine complex includes:
- **Asuka Kannabi Shrine**
- **Yuga Mountain Cherry and Maple Poem Monument**
- **Sarutahiko Shrine**
- **Kuebiko Shrine**
- **Hitokoto Inari Shrine**
- **The "Sacred Mountain" area**, which enshrines **Ōsugi Daimyōjin, Shiratama Daimyōjin, Suehiro Daimyōjin,** and **Koganemaru Daimyōjin**{{sfn|奈良市史 社寺編|pp=80-81}}

== 祭神 ==
=== 本殿 ===
* {{ill|Ukanomitama-no-Mikoto|ja|宇迦御魂大神}}

=== 境内社 ===
* **Asuka Kannabi Shrine** – Enshrining the **gentle spirit** (*nigimitama*) of Yuga Daigongen.
* **Sarutahiko Shrine** – Enshrining {{ill|Sarutahiko-no-Mikoto|ja|猿田彦大神}}
* **Kuebiko Shrine** – Enshrining {{ill|Kuebiko-no-Kami|ja|久延毘古}}
* **Hitokoto Inari Shrine**

== 関連項目 ==
{{Commonscat|Yuga Shrine|瑜伽神社}}
{{osm box|w|343366364}}
* {{ill|Naramachi|ja|ならまち}}

