The original **guardian shrine** of **Gango-ji Zenjō-in** was **Tenmangū Shrine**, which remained Daijō-in’s protector.{{sfn|『大乗院寺社雑事記』にみえる瀧蔵社と新宮社|p=47}}

In *Kyōhō* 3 (1718), a shrine caretaker received a divine dream and restored a **small Inari shrine** within **Tenmangū Shrine**.{{sfn|『大乗院寺社雑事記』にみえる瀧蔵社と新宮社|p=48}} Since Yuga Shrine and **Inari shrines** both enshrine **Ukanomitama-no-Mikoto**, it is speculated that this Inari Shrine later became known as Yuga Shrine.{{sfn|『大乗院寺社雑事記』にみえる瀧蔵社と新宮社|p=48}}

=== 瑜伽山城 ===
This area is also believed to be the site of **Yuga Castle** (瑜伽山城), also called **Seihōin-yama Castle** or **Kion-zan Castle**, with remains of wide terraces and moats still visible.{{sfn|奈良市史 社寺編|p=81}}

== 境内 ==
The shrine complex includes:
- **Asuka Kannabi Shrine**
- **Yuga Mountain Cherry and Maple Poem Monument**
- **Sarutahiko Shrine**
- **Kuebiko Shrine**
- **Hitokoto Inari Shrine**
- **The "Sacred Mountain" area**, which enshrines **Ōsugi Daimyōjin, Shiratama Daimyōjin, Suehiro Daimyōjin,** and **Koganemaru Daimyōjin**{{sfn|奈良市史 社寺編|pp=80-81}}

